00:22:59,470 --> 00:23:09,600
But then we say, “This is intolerable!”
Then I’m saying of Gurudev. He would say

178
00:23:09,600 --> 00:23:16,039
as he sat beneath ‘tṛṇād api sunīchena
taror api sahiṣṇunā amāninā mānadena

179
00:23:16,039 --> 00:23:23,380
kīrttanīyaḥ sadā hariḥ’ (Śrī Śikṣāṣṭakam
3). The taror iva sahiṣṇunā, be more

180
00:23:23,380 --> 00:23:31,380
tolerant than a tree. He said, “It means
tolerating what is intolerable.” Because,

181
00:23:31,380 --> 00:23:35,910
if you can tolerate something that is just
difficult to tolerate, that is one level.

182
00:23:35,910 --> 00:23:42,679
He ratcheted it up to another level. He said,
“What it means is — tolerating which is

183
00:23:42,679 --> 00:23:51,149
intolerable.” That is a higher level. [LAUGHING]
He said, “Or honoring someone who’s not

184
00:23:51,149 --> 00:23:58,389
worthy of honor,” in the conventional sense.

185
00:23:58,389 --> 00:24:04,779
So, the first line of defence — toleration.

186
00:24:04,779 --> 00:24:14,250
But you can tell that it almost, in some instances,
has a little bit of lingering resentment or

187
00:24:14,250 --> 00:24:21,649
begrudging like ‘alright, I have to tolerate
this.’ But Guru Mahārāja would tell us,

188
00:24:21,649 --> 00:24:28,740
“In the Bhāgavatam it takes it to another
level.” That’s in the Brahmā-stuti, the

189
00:24:28,740 --> 00:24:29,980
Prayers of Brahmā:

190
00:24:29,980 --> 00:24:36,360
tat te ’nukampāṁ su-samīkṣamāṇo
bhuñjāna evātma-kṛtaṁ vipākam

191
00:24:36,360 --> 00:24:44,570
hṛd-vāg-vapurbhir vidadhan namas te
jīveta yo mukti-pade sa dāya-bhāk

192
00:24:44,570 --> 00:24:55,730
So here it’s saying, from a deeper level
of seeing and interpretation. We’ll remember

193
00:24:55,730 --> 00:25:00,549
earlier in the Gītā it’s said after ‘bhoktāraṁ
yajña-tapasāṁ sarva-loka-maheśvaram’

194
00:25:00,549 --> 00:25:06,690
next line ‘suhṛdaṁ sarva-bhūtānāṁ’
(Bhagavad-gītā 5.29), “Yes, everything

195
00:25:06,690 --> 00:25:13,460
is meant for My enjoyment; yes, I’m in control
of everything?” “Even these unhappy circumstances

196
00:25:13,460 --> 00:25:19,490
that are happening?” “Ultimately, yes!”
What is next line? Suhṛdaṁ, suhṛd — “But

197
00:25:19,490 --> 00:25:26,169
I’m your best friend, I’m your dearest
friend, more than you realize or know.”

198
00:25:26,169 --> 00:25:32,029
So that means, whatever’s happening to you
is not unfriendly. Krishna is not inimical

199
00:25:32,029 --> 00:25:45,210
to us. This is not Judeo-Christian God who
is always like ‘do what I say or you’re

200
00:25:45,210 --> 00:25:56,180
going to get a stick,’ punishment. There’re
instances, known instances, where Krishna’s

201
00:25:56,180 --> 00:26:04,139
taken his flute and tapped the cowherd boy.
But they like that. [LAUGHING] And the flute

202
00:26:04,139 --> 00:26:13,809
is made out of chinmoy. So, it’s not that
‘rod of chastisement’ of the scary God.

203
00:26:13,809 --> 00:26:20,640
He’s saying, “I’m your dearest friend.”
So, then that means, whatever is happening

204
00:26:20,640 --> 00:26:34,740
to us, even unpleasant, is not, with malintention,
is not meant to take us down and therefore

205
00:26:34,740 --> 00:26:37,200
friendly.

206
00:26:37,200 --> 00:26:46,649
When I remember in school. It probably goes
by various names like ‘a pop-quiz,’ ‘a

207
00:26:46,649 --> 00:26:52,480
flash- quiz,’ where the teacher would suddenly
tell the students, “All right, class, close

208
00:26:52,480 --> 00:27:00,990
your books.” And everybody groans, “Oh,
no! Why?” As some people think, “Our teacher

209
00:27:00,990 --> 00:27:09,019
is mean. Why is she doing it to us?” It’s
not because she’s mean but what she’s

210
00:27:09,019 --> 00:27:16,860
realized is although everyone’s making a
show of reading the book, the subject materials,

211
00:27:16,860 --> 00:27:24,590
asking questions, answering questions, she’s
uncertain how much they’re actually absorbing.

212
00:27:24,590 --> 00:27:31,830
“Now close the books. I’m going to give
you a little pop-quiz-flash-quiz (whatever

213
00:27:31,830 --> 00:27:39,120
